Although they are considered rare disorders, muscular dystrophies have a strong 
impact on people's health. Increased disease severity with age, frequently 
accompanied by the loss of ability to walk in some people, and the lack of 
treatment, have directed the researchers towards the development of more 
effective therapeutic strategies aimed to improve the quality of life and life 
expectancy, slow down the progression, and delay the onset or convert a severe 
phenotype into a milder one. Improved understanding of the complex pathology of 
these diseases together with the tremendous advances in molecular biology 
technologies has led to personalized therapeutic procedures. Different 
approaches that are currently under extensive investigation require more 
efficient, sensitive, and less invasive methods. Due to its remarkable 
analytical sensitivity, droplet digital PCR has become a promising tool for 
accurate measurement of biomarkers that monitor disease progression and 
quantification of various therapeutic efficiency and can be considered a tool 
for non-invasive prenatal diagnosis and newborn screening. Here, we summarize 
the recent applications of droplet digital PCR in muscular dystrophy research 
and discuss the factors that should be considered to get the best performance 
with this technology.

